<HEAD>Panel Hands Agent Orange Decision Back to Derwinski</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterans Secretary Edward J. Derwinski will
have to decide without the guidance he was looking for from an
advisory panel whether to award benefits to some Vietnam veterans
exposed to Agent Orange.
   Derwinski is expected to make the decision around Thanksgiving
as the result of court-ordered regulations for determining the
relationship between exposure to the herbicide exposure and cancer.
   Nearly 12,000 disability claims once denied by the VA are now
pending as a result of a court order issued in May by U.S. District
Judge Thelton E. Henderson in San Francisco.
   Derwinski was looking for the Environmental Hazards Advisory
Committee, made up largely of scientists, to clear up some of the
arguments over Agent Orange.
   But the panel, in its first ruling on Agent Orange, acknowledged
Friday that it couldn't come up with a definite conclusion. The
committee said it ``does not find the evidence sufficient at the
present time to conclude that there is a significant statistical
association between exposure to (Agent Orange) and non-Hodgkins
lymphoma.''
   They added they ``cannot rule out such an association.''
   Veterans' groups blame Agent Orange for cancers that have turned
up years later in former soldiers who were exposed when the United
States used it to clear jungle area in Vietnam during the war.
   Veterans say their non-Hodgkins lymphoma, soft tissue sarcoma
and other forms of cancer were caused by the defoliant.
   The government has long said that cancers cannot be definitively
linked to Agent Orange. No studies have been undertaken looking at
veterans who were exposed to the chemical because government
scientists contend they cannot create such a sample.
   In his ruling in May, Henderson said the VA had used criteria
more stringent than Congress intended in a 1984 law that ordered
benefits to veterans exposed to the herbicide.
   The VA has said the new regulations give Derwinski the freedom
to give veterans the benefit of the doubt absent any strong
recommendation by the committee, made up largely of scientists.
   The committee will meet in late January to address studies
covering Agent Orange exposure and soft tissue sarcomas as well as
porphyria cutanea tarda, an ailment that produces chronic skin
lesions. Those are the other two ailments addressed in Henderson's
court ruling.
   Several of Derwinski's actions have been interpreted as signs
that he wants to take action, if only limited, in favor of
veterans. Those include his decision not to appeal the May ruling,
his appointment of retired Adm. Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr. as a special
adviser and his statements that he will give veterans the benefit
of the doubt.
   Zumwalt ordered spraying of Agent Orange during the war, and a
son who served in Vietnam died of a cancer believed linked to
exposure.
   The American Legion, which has accused the panel of bias,
criticized Friday's statement.
   ``They spent entirely too much time on crossing the t's and
dotting the i's,'' said Richard S. Christian, a deputy director of
the American Legion.
   The main suspect in Agent Orange is the contaminant dioxin, a
byproduct of industrial processes known to be an extremely potent
carcinogen in laboratory animals. Its effects on humans are less
well documented.
   Of the roughly 230,000 veterans who have told VA they were
exposed to Agent Orange, 635 have documented cases of non-Hodgkins
lymphoma, the VA says.
   There are 35,000 veterans seeking benefits for problems linked
to Agent Orange exposure.
</TEXT>
