<HEAD>Report Links Agent Orange to Cancer, Other Diseases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, `About 35,000 ...,' to CLARIFY that those
deal with all illnesses, not just non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Picks up
12th graf pvs, `About 240,000 ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three kinds of cancer and five other diseases
among Vietnam veterans can be traced to exposure to the defoliant
Agent Orange, according to a scientific report released Tuesday by
veterans groups.
   The report, released on the eve of a congressional hearing on a
bill to pay benefits to Agent Orange victims, produced no new
evidence. Rather, it reviewed existing studies.
   Lawmakers pushing the benefits praised the study by the Agent
Orange Task Force, seven scientists assembled by the American
Legion, Vietnam Veterans of America and the National Veterans Legal
Services Program.
   ``It is not only appropriate but it is scientifically correct''
to award compensation to Vietnam veterans exposed to the
dioxin-containing defoliant, said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., a
Vietnam veteran and sponsor of Senate legislation to award
compensation.
   The report said proof exists of a ``significant statistical
association'' between herbicide exposure and non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma; soft-tissue sarcoma; chloracne and other skin disorders;
early liver disease; and porphyria cutanea tarda, a metabolic
disorder.
   The scientists also said there was enough evidence to give the
benefit of the doubt in awarding compensation to veterans who were
exposed and suffer from Hodgkin's disease, neurologic and
reproductive problems and developmental problems with their
offspring.
   They say there's limited evidence of an association between
exposure and a large number of cancers, as well as immunological
abnormalities and psychological problems.
   A Senate bill has been passed and a House bill introduced to
provide benefits to veterans who claim their diseases were a result
of exposure. The bills differ in cost _ $36 million for the Senate
version and $89 million for the House version _ length of coverage
and number of diseases covered.
   A Veterans Affairs subcommittee was scheduled to hear testimony
Wednesday on the House bill sponsored by Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill., a
co-chairman of the Vietnam-Era Veterans in Congress.
   Both bills would create an independent panel of scientists under
the auspices of the independent National Academy of Sciences to
review herbicide studies. Critics say the government has
intentionally tried to influence the evidence on Agent Orange to
avoid paying benefits.
   VA Secretary Edward J. Derwinski has decided to award benefits
to non-Hodgkin's lymphoma sufferers who served in Vietnam. That
decision was made March 29 as the result of a study by the Centers
for Disease Control.
   About 35,000 veterans have filed claims asserting a connection
between exposure and a variety of ailments. Only a handful _ those
for chloracne _ have been granted.
   About 240,000 veterans believe they may have been exposed to the
herbicide and have requested physical examinations, VA says. A
total of 12 million gallons of Agent Orange was sprayed during the
war to remove ground cover and crops.
   Agent Orange is a phenoxyacetic herbicide contaminated with
dioxin during manufacture. Dioxin is the main disease-causing
suspect.
   The Environmental Protection Agency has labeled dioxin a
``probable human carcinogen.''
   The scientists on the panel say an influential private study of
Nitro, W.Va., Monsanto workers exposed to dioxin has been
discredited because of allegations of scientific fraud. So has an
important study of industrial workers in Ludwigshafen, West
Germany, they said.
   The scientists were especially critical of the VA and CDC for
ignoring animal studies, especially because agencies such as the
EPA gives them such strong consideration.
   VA scientists say the animal dioxin studies are less reliable
because of the variety of reactions from species to species, and
because there is documented human exposure, said VA spokeswoman
Donna St. John.
   The two bills cover only a few of the ailments: non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma, soft-tissue sarcoma, melanoma and chloracne. The House
version adds melanoma and basal cell carcinoma.
   Oliver Meadows, the chairman of the VA's outside Environmental
Hazards Advisory Committee, dismissed criticism in the new report
that it ignored a large number of studies and that it used a
``simplistic tallying system'' to weigh data.
   The panel has only examined the connection between Agent Orange
and non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. The new report covers all the possible
ailments.
   The panel found in November that an association cannot be proved
or disproved. The VA panel meets later this month to consider other
cancer studies.
   The CDC study of six kinds kinds of cancer found an increased
risk of only one _ non-Hodgkin's lymphoma _ among Vietnam veterans.
It found no such increase in soft tissue sarcoma, Hodgkin's
disease, and nasal, nasopharyngeal and primary liver cancer.
   The study looked only indirectly at Agent Orange exposure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

