<HEAD>Report Criticizes VA's Refusal to Compensate Agent Orange-Related
Illness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report to Veterans Secretary Edward J.
Derwinski sharply criticizes the government for its longstanding
refusal to compensate Vietnam veterans for illnesses linked to
Agent Orange exposure.
   The report by Admiral Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr. was released the same
day an advisory panel to the Department of Veterans Affairs paved
the way for compensation to Vietnam veterans suffering from a rare
cancer known as soft-tissue sarcoma.
   Derwinski is expected to decide in late May or early June
whether to award compensation for that form of cancer.
   ``I hope this is the beginning of the end of the nightmare Agent
Orange victims have suffered,'' said Sen. Thomas A. Daschle,
D-S.D., a co-chair of the Vietnam-Era Veterans in Congress caucus.
   The VA Advisory Committee on Environmental Hazards made its
recommendation Thursday after reviewing scientific studies on the
connection between dioxin and herbicide exposure to soft tissue
sarcoma.
   Zumwalt, one of four lay members of the 15-member panel,
criticized the committee Wednesday for its previous handling of the
Agent Orange question. The panel was created by Congress in 1984 to
investigate the link between exposure and a host of ailments,
largely cancers, that Vietnam veterans have been complaining about
since the 1970s.
   A federal court order last year, which Derwinski declined to
appeal, forced the panel to begin its work anew. Although the last
Agent Orange was sprayed in 1971, the VA has awarded only a handful
of Agent Orange claims, and those were all for a skin condition
called chloracne.
   Derwinski decided in March that all Vietnam veterans with
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma should be compensated.
   The American Legion, the Vietnam Veterans of America and outside
scientists commissioned by the two groups have long criticized the
government's refusal to acknowledge health hazards associated with
Agent Orange. The herbicide was contaminated with dioxin, labeled a
``probable human carcinogen'' by the Environmental Protection
Agency.
   On Thursday, the VA released a report that Zumwalt compiled for
Derwinski.
   ``Were the faulty conclusions, flawed methodology and noticeable
bias of the advisory committee an isolated problem, correcting the
misdirection would be more manageable,'' Zumwalt wrote.
   ``But, experience with other governmental agencies responsible
for specifically analyzing and studying the effects of exposure to
Agent Orange strongly hints at a discernible pattern, if not
outright governmental collaboration, to deny compensation to
Vietnam veterans associated with exposure to dioxin,'' he wrote.
   Zumwalt referred to the federal Centers for Disease Control,
given responsibility by Congress for conducting Agent Orange
studies because of ``evidence of VA's footdragging.''
   Zumwalt repeated allegations raised in a congressional hearing
last summer that CDC sabotaged its Agent Orange study, suggesting
``that political pressures once again interfered with the kind of
professional, unbiased review Congress had sought to obtain.''
   Compensation for Agent Orange will cost nearly $90 million for
only a few of the ailments linked to the herbicide, the
Congressional Budget Office says.
   CDC has maintained it cannot establish who among Vietnam
veterans was exposed to Agent Orange, making further study
impossible.
   Zumwalt said his own review of the scientific evidence suggests
28 ailments, mostly cancers, can be linked to Agent Orange exposure.
   Zumwalt, commander of naval forces in Vietnam, ordered the
spraying of the defoliant in Vietnam and lost a son, a Vietnam
veteran, to a cancer linked to Agent Orange exposure. Zumwalt has
said he nonetheless would have ordered the spraying because it
ultimately saved more lives than it cost.
   Zumwalt said the herbicide was used in undiluted form to remove
enemy cover, destroy enemy crops and clear vegetation around
military installations, landing zones, fire base camps and trails.
   He said more was sprayed than records indicate, because of
unofficial uses of the herbicide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

