<HEAD>Zumwalt Says Much More Defoliant Sprayed Than Recorded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More Agent Orange was sprayed in Vietnam than
official records show, a former commander said in a report Thursday
that also suggests ``a discernible pattern, if not collaboration,''
to deny veterans compensation.
   Also, a Veterans Affairs Department panel issued a ruling that
brings compensation closer to veterans exposed to the herbicide who
suffer from soft-tissue sarcoma, a rare cancer.
   Admiral Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr., in his report to Veterans Secretary
Edward J. Derwinski, said he was certain from his experience that
more Agent Orange was spread than recorded.
   ``Combat units ... frequently conducted `unofficial' sprayings
of Agent Orange obtained from out of channel, and thus unrecorded
sources.'' said Zumwalt.
   ``Additionally, as commander, U.S. Naval Forces, Vietnam, I was
aware that Agent Orange issued to Allied forces was frequently used
on unrecorded missions,'' Zumwalt said in the report.
   The report, issued May 6, was released Thursday, a day after
Zumwalt told an advisory panel to the VA he believes that 28
diseases are linked to Agent Orange exposure. Zumwalt, a special
adviser to Derwinski, was recently named to the department's
Advisory Committee on Environmental Hazards.
   The panel on Thursday determined it is as likely as not that a
significant association exists between soft-tissue sarcoma and
Agent Orange exposure.
   Derwinski is to decide by June whether to award disability
payments to veterans with that disease. Derwinski decided in March
that all Vietnam veterans with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma should be
compensated.
   The advisory committee in August will examine studies relating
dioxin and herbicide exposure to a skin disease known as chloracne,
and a metabolic disorder known as porphyrea cutanea tarda.
   The two reports make it likely that veterans will be compensated
for soft-tissue sarcoma. VA spokesman Bonner Day said the
department had no figure on how many Agent Orange claimants said
they have soft-tissue sarcoma.
   Zumwalt's report said the herbicide was used in strengths far in
excess of that suggested by the manufacturers. The makers have
settled a class-action lawsuit brought by afflicted veterans.
   He also criticizes government actions and studies on Agent
Orange, including the activities of the advisory panel.
   His broadsides backed up claims by veterans who have been trying
to get compensation for more than a decade and who claim the
government has had to be pushed to move and has ignored evidence
supporting links between Agent Orange and cancers.
   ``Were the faulty conclusions, faulty methodology and noticeable
bias of the advisory committee an isolated problem, correcting the
misdirection would be more manageable,'' Zumwalt wrote.
   ``But, experience with other governmental agencies responsible
for ... analyzing and studying the effects of exposure to Agent
Orange strongly hints at a discernible pattern, if not outright
governmental collaboration, to deny compensation to Vietnam
veterans for disabilities associated with exposure to dioxin.''
   Committee chairman Oliver Meadows said he would not comment on
the Zumwalt report.
   Zumwalt ordered the spraying of the defoliant in Vietnam and
lost a son, a Vietnam veteran, to a cancer linked to Agent Orange
exposure.
   About 12 million gallons of the herbicide, which contained
cancer-causing dioxin, was sprayed from 1965 to 1970, according to
records.
   Zumwalt said, however, ``a significant, if not major source of
exposure was from non-recorded, non-Ranch Hand operations.'' Ranch
Hand was the name for the aircraft spraying operation.
   ``Evidence readily suggests that at the time experts knew that
Agent Orange was harmful to military personnel,'' he said.
   Zumwalt said that in addition to removing enemy cover and
destroying crops, the herbicide was sprayed to clear vegetation
around military installations, landing zones, fire base camps and
trails.
</TEXT>
