<HEAD>Scientists Testify That Weedkillers May be More Harmful Than
Thought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Garry in 7th graf and Shelia in 10th graf are cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers and homeowners frequently use
weedkillers that contain a key ingredient of Agent Orange that may
be more harmful than previously thought, scientists told a
congressional panel Tuesday.
   ``It appears to me that there are other contaminants in
herbicides, as well as herbicides per se, which have not been
adequately evaluated for carcinogenicity in animals let alone
studied for their effect ... in humans,'' Daniel Thau Teitelbaum, a
Denver physician, told a House Government Operations subcommittee.
   Teitelbaum studied industry records as part of the class-action
lawsuit by Vietnam veterans against the makers of Agent Orange.
   In the 20 years of controversy surrounding whether the
government should pay benefits to ailing Vietnam veterans who were
exposed to Agent Orange, attention has focused on dioxin
contamination 2,4,5-T _ one of the herbicide's two key ingredients.
   The Environmental Protection Agency has labeled dioxin a
``probable human carcinogen'' and 2,4,5-T has been out of
circulation for years.
   But scientists told the subcommittee that the other key
ingredient _ 2,4-D _ causes cancers and other ailments linked to
Agent Orange. Evidence shows that 2,4-D was also contaminated with
harmful compounds, some related to dioxin, according to testimony
on the government handling of Agent Orange research.
   The farm-chemical industry says ongoing research into 2,4-D is
needed but that the ``weight of the evidence'' so far indicates the
risk of harm is relatively small if it does indeed exist, industry
spokesman Garry Hamlin said in a telephone interview from
Indianapolis.
   A so-called phenoxy herbicide, 2,4-D is sold over the counter to
kill dandelions and other lawn weeds. Farmers use it against weeds
in corn, wheat, rice and sorghum.
   Teitelbaum, noting that use of 2,4,5-T was first discontinued
because of concern about birth defects, said studies were needed on
possible birth defects resulting from 2,4-D exposure.
   Two National Cancer Institute studies have shown an increased
risk of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a rare cancer, in ``frequent users
of agriculture chemicals,'' said NCI researcher Shelia Hoar Zahm.
   The studies of farm workers in Kansas and Nebraska found that
the risk grows or drops according to skin exposure and how soon
after exposure the worker changed clothes.
   Vietnam veterans were exposed to Agent Orange in concentrations
far in excess of the normal strength, special adviser Elmo R.
Zumwalt Jr. has told the Veterans Affairs Department.
   The department said this year it would compensate veterans for
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and for another rare cancer _ soft tissue
sarcoma. However, the government maintains that exposure can't be
documented.
   Zumwalt, a retired admiral, ordered Agent Orange sprayed in
Vietnam to clear dense jungle. His son, who served in Vietnam,
later died of cancer, which Zumwalt attributes to Agent Orange. he
said 27 ailments can be linked to Agent Orange.
   Zumwalt, appearing before the subcommittee on human resources
and intergovernmental relations, reiterated his contention that
government and industry officials ``intentionally manipulated or
withheld compelling information on the adverse health effects
associated with exposure to the toxic contaminants contained in
Agent Orange.''
   In a related matter, Rep. Ted R. Weiss, D-N.Y., said his
subcommittee had forced the Air Force to release a 4-year-old draft
report showing an increase of birth defects among the offspring of
those who handled and sprayed Agent Orange from the air.
   Patti Turner, a spokeswoman for the Air Force Surgeon General's
office, said the conclusions were premature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

