<HEAD>Senators Optimistic About Agent Orange Benefits Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators advocating disability benefits for
Vietnam veterans suffering from cancer they believe caused by Agent
Orange said Thursday they were confident of finally winning
congressional passage after repeated setbacks.
   Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., said the compromise bill would
provide interim disability benefits to veterans who were exposed to
the chemical defoliant during the Vietnam War and now suffer from
either non-Hodgkin's lymphoma or soft-tissue sarcoma.
   Under the bill, disability benefits would extend only through
1993. Survivors' benefits for spouses would go through mid-April
1992. Congress, which by then would have received a new study by the
Centers for Disease Control, would have to vote to continue the
benefits.
   The measure is needed ``not only to help veterans with their
medical difficulties, but it is also important as a statement that
we intend to make good on our promises to help those who fought in
the war,'' said Kerry, a former Navy lieutenant who piloted a patrol
boat in the Mekong Delta.
   ``Too many veterans remember what it was like to fight the VC
(Viet Cong) They didn't have to come back here to fight the VA
(Veterans Administration, the name still used for the Veterans
Department),'' the senator said.
   Separate Agent Orange bills sponsored by Kerry and Sen. Thomas
Daschle, D-S.D., failed in 1987 and again last year. The Reagan
administration steadfastly opposed the proposals, saying more
scientific evidence was needed to link the chemical defoliant used
by U.S. forces in Southeast Asia to the cancers in the light of
several studies that failed to find such a link.
   But Kerry and Daschle, at a news conference introducing the
legislation, said positive signs from both the new administration
and Capitol Hill account for their optimism.
   The senators said they were encouraged by Veterans Affairs
Secretary Ed Derwinski and his decision last month not to appeal a
federal appeals court's decision striking down regulations to
restrict compensation for Agent Orange victims.
   Derwinski also ordered reviews of the cases of all Vietnam
veterans whose Agent Orange claims were denied. Daschle praised
Derwinski as the ``most sympathetic'' head of the Veterans
Administration since the Vietnam War.
   The bill's prospects improved when Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.,
chairman of the Senate Veterans' Affairs, backed it late last year
after various changes to narrow its scope.
   The measure would cost an estimated $19 million annually in
benefits, Senate aides said.
</TEXT>
