<HL> Letters to the Editor:
Agent Orange</HL>
<DD> 12/11/86</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV) </IN>
<TEXT>
   I recently read William R. Havender's review (Bookshelf, Nov. 11) of "Dioxin, Agent Orange: The Facts" by Michael Gough. 
Mr. Havender states that, based on the information in this book, my father, Adm. E. R. Zumwalt Jr., need not feel guilt for his son's and grandson's tragic health problems. 

   I agree that my father should not feel guilty about these problems and that only animal studies to date show birth defects. 
However, the conclusion that the evidence of cancer in Vietnam vets from Agent Orange is exceedingly rare and a result from whatever it is that causes these conditions among ordinary Americans of similar age may need to be modified in the light of the most recent scientific study. 
That study, in the Sept. 5 Journal of the American Medical Association, states, "Men exposed to herbicides more than twenty days per year had a sixfold increased risk of NHL (non-Hodgkins lymphoma) . . . relative to nonfarmers." 
A reading of that article and the editorial published with it clearly indicates that a study by the National Cancer Institute demonstrates that Kansas farmers who used 2,4-D, one of the two principal elements in Agent Orange, without protective gear had six times more non-Hodgkins lymphoma. 

   Although Mr. Havender did a fine review of Mr. Gough's book and presented some of the facts regarding Agent Orange, I believe your readers will be interested in the most recent scientific data. 

   Elmo R. Zumwalt III
   Fayetteville, N.C.
</TEXT>
