<LEADPARA>  By a 99-0 vote, the Senate passed legislation Wednesday to provide permanent
disability benefits for Vietnam War veterans suffering from three specific
diseases tied to exposure to the herbicide Agent Orange. Administration
officials said earlier this week that President Bush would sign the measure.
The bill, which cleared the House by a 412-0 vote Tuesday, ensures that
veterans who suffer from non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, soft-tissue sarcoma and
chloracne, three diseases tied by scientists to Agent Orange, will qualify for
benefits. Payments may be available for victims of other diseases if the
National Academy of Sciences concludes that exposure to the herbicide, a
dioxin-based chemical that was used to thin jungle cover, caused or
contributed to their illness.  </LEADPARA>
