<LEADPARA>  President Bush, praising the U.S. military in the Persian Gulf as well as in
past wars, today ended a two-decade dispute by signing a bill to compensate
Vietnam War veterans exposed to Agent Orange.;    "A grateful nation salutes
our veterans," Bush said at a White House signing ceremony. He also signed a
bill giving a 5.4 percent cost-of-living increase in veterans benefits.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  AGENT ORANGE BILL GETS BUSH OK  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The Agent Orange measure permanently extends disability benefits to Vietnam
veterans suffering from two types of cancer presumed to be caused by the
herbicide, non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and soft-tissue sarcoma.;    Agent Orange
was sprayed by U.S. troops in Vietnam to defoliate jungle cover. For years,
the government refused to recognize a link between the herbicide and these
diseases.;    While some controversy still remains over the effect of Agent
Orange and its primary component, dioxin, the bill came to Bush's desk with
the unanimous approval of both the House and Senate.;    Sponsors of the bill
said Iraq's threat to use chemical and biological weapons against allied
troops contributed to the margin of passage.  </TEXT>
